    <text>
        <body>
            <head>216. Telegram From the Delegation to the <rs type="event"
                    corresp="recdBCWoByS1vPFiZ">Nuclear and Space Talks</rs> in Geneva to the
                    <orgName corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">Department of State</orgName>
                <note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d216fn1">Source: Department of State,
                    Central Foreign Policy File, D870879–0425. Secret; Priority; <gloss
                        target="#t_EXDIS_1">Exdis</gloss>. Sent Priority for information to Moscow,
                    the Mission to <gloss target="#t_NATO_1">
                        <orgName corresp="rec9wzMIGHUgT4FsE">NATO</orgName>
                    </gloss>, and <gloss target="#t_USNMR_1">USNMR</gloss>
                    <gloss target="#t_SHAPE_1">SHAPE</gloss>.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Geneva</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1987-10-26T15:54:00+00:00">October 26, 1987, 1554<gloss
                            target="#t_Z_1">Z</gloss>
                    </date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <p>11335. Subject: <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss>: <persName corresp="recJgMRnt6OpkXR5T">Lehman</persName>-<persName
                    corresp="recg40EWOB1iEMjYn">Vorontsov</persName>/<persName
                    corresp="recpzeNUmrT8bK2yc">Obukhov</persName> conversation, October 23,
                1987.</p>
            <p>1. This is <gloss target="#t_NST_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recdBCWoByS1vPFiZ">NST</rs>
                </gloss>/<gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss>
                <gloss target="#t_MEMCON_1">Memcon</gloss> VIII-M-145. Secret—Entire Text.</p>
            <p>2. Meeting date: October 23, 1987. Place: Foreign Ministers meeting, Moscow</p>
            <pb facs="0955" n="928" xml:id="pg_928"/>
            <p>3. Participants:</p>
            <table cols="2">
                <row>
                    <cell>U.S.</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <gloss target="#t_USSR_1">USSR</gloss>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Ambassador <persName corresp="recJgMRnt6OpkXR5T">Lehman</persName>
                    </cell>
                    <cell>Ambassador <persName corresp="recg40EWOB1iEMjYn">Vorontsov</persName>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell/>
                    <cell>Ambassador <persName corresp="recpzeNUmrT8bK2yc">Obukhov</persName>
                    </cell>
                </row>
            </table>
            <p>4. Summary: <persName corresp="recg40EWOB1iEMjYn">Vorontsov</persName> went out of
                his way, at the conclusion of the <persName corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN"
                    >Shultz</persName>-<persName corresp="reczYQHQnMCD2hSLc">Shevardnadze</persName>
                meeting on October 23, to say to <persName corresp="recJgMRnt6OpkXR5T"
                    >Lehman</persName> that the U.S. has been “given what it asked for” on <rs
                    corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19" type="topic">sublimits</rs>. When asked a direct
                question, he seemed to agree that this meant acceptance of the U.S.-proposed <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04">ballistic missile</rs>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warhead</rs> and <gloss
                    target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                </gloss>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warhead</rs>
                <rs corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19" type="topic">sublimits</rs> of 4800 and 3300.
                    <persName corresp="recpzeNUmrT8bK2yc">Obukhov</persName> is supposed to make
                things clear in <rs type="event" corresp="recdBCWoByS1vPFiZ">Geneva</rs>. End
                Summary.</p>
            <p>5. As Ambassadors <persName corresp="recJgMRnt6OpkXR5T">Lehman</persName> and
                    <persName corresp="recpzeNUmrT8bK2yc">Obukhov</persName> were leaving the room
                following Secretary <persName corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName>’s final
                meeting with Foreign Minister <persName corresp="reczYQHQnMCD2hSLc"
                    >Shevardnadze</persName> on October 23<note n="2" place="foot" xml:id="d216fn2">
                    <persName corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="reczYQHQnMCD2hSLc">Shevardnadze</persName>’s concluding session
                    took place in the Guest House of the Soviet Foreign Ministry from 5:10 to 6:20
                    p.m. The memorandum of conversation is printed in <ref
                        target="frus1981-88v06#d85">
                        <hi rendition="simple_italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1981–1988, vol. VI,
                        Soviet Union, October 1986–January 1989, Document 85</ref>.</note> in
                Moscow, <persName corresp="recJgMRnt6OpkXR5T">Lehman</persName> asked <persName
                    corresp="recpzeNUmrT8bK2yc">Obukhov</persName> if he could explain General
                Secretary <persName corresp="recXTrNyt2vU9QpAl">Gorbachev</persName>’s proposal on
                    <rs corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19" type="topic">sublimits</rs> (septel). <persName
                    corresp="recpzeNUmrT8bK2yc">Obukhov</persName> said that it would be best to
                discuss this matter in <rs type="event" corresp="recdBCWoByS1vPFiZ">Geneva</rs>.
                    <persName corresp="recJgMRnt6OpkXR5T">Lehman</persName> said that he hoped the
                Soviet side would introduce the proposal quickly in <rs type="event"
                    corresp="recdBCWoByS1vPFiZ">Geneva</rs>, because <persName
                    corresp="recJgMRnt6OpkXR5T">Lehman</persName> was not certain that he understood
                the proposal. <persName corresp="recpzeNUmrT8bK2yc">Obukhov</persName> said that he
                and <persName corresp="recJgMRnt6OpkXR5T">Lehman</persName> could discuss <rs
                    corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19" type="topic">sublimits</rs> in detail as soon as
                they return to <rs type="event" corresp="recdBCWoByS1vPFiZ">Geneva</rs>.<note n="3"
                    place="foot" xml:id="d216fn3">In telegram 11766 from <gloss target="#t_NST_1">
                        <rs type="event" corresp="recdBCWoByS1vPFiZ">NST</rs>
                    </gloss> Geneva, November 5, <persName corresp="recJgMRnt6OpkXR5T"
                        >Lehman</persName> reported on a luncheon of November 3, where “<persName
                        corresp="recpzeNUmrT8bK2yc">Obukhov</persName> described the recent Soviet
                        <rs type="topic" corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19">sublimit</rs> proposal as being
                    a ‘concession’ designed to meet U.S. concerns.” (Department of State, Central
                    Foreign Policy File, D870913–0587)</note>
            </p>
            <p>6. At this point <persName corresp="recJgMRnt6OpkXR5T">Lehman</persName> overheard
                Deputy Foreign Minister <persName corresp="recg40EWOB1iEMjYn">Vorontsov</persName>
                say “excuse me, I have to talk to this gentleman.” <persName
                    corresp="recg40EWOB1iEMjYn">Vorontsov</persName> pushed several of his Soviet
                colleagues aside, and said to <persName corresp="recJgMRnt6OpkXR5T"
                    >Lehman</persName> “you owe me for this one. I have arranged for you to get your
                    <rs corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19" type="topic">sublimits</rs>. I just wanted you
                to know that our discussion of <rs corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19" type="topic"
                    >sublimits</rs> was not in vain. You have received what you wanted on <rs
                    corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19" type="topic">sublimits</rs>.”</p>
            <p>7. <persName corresp="recJgMRnt6OpkXR5T">Lehman</persName> responded that the
                proposal was not clear to him. While the numbers proposed by the Soviet side seemed
                similar to U.S. proposals, the Soviet side’s structure seems to go down a path that
                strays from the direction both sides seem headed down in <rs type="event"
                    corresp="recdBCWoByS1vPFiZ">Geneva</rs>. <persName corresp="recg40EWOB1iEMjYn"
                    >Vorontsov</persName> replied, “no Ron, we have given you what you asked for.”
                    <persName corresp="recJgMRnt6OpkXR5T">Lehman</persName> asked <persName
                    corresp="recg40EWOB1iEMjYn">Vorontsov</persName> “are you saying that you agree
                to our proposal of a <rs type="topic" corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19">sublimit</rs> of
                4800 on total <rs type="topic" corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04">ballistic missile</rs>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs> and under that a <pb
                    facs="0956" n="929" xml:id="pg_929"/>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19">sublimit</rs> of 3300 on <gloss
                    target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                </gloss> and on <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                </gloss> only”? <persName corresp="recg40EWOB1iEMjYn">Vorontsov</persName> responded
                “yes, you have what you want.”</p>
            <p>8. At this point <persName corresp="recJgMRnt6OpkXR5T">Lehman</persName> grabbed
                    <persName corresp="recpzeNUmrT8bK2yc">Obukhov</persName>, who had been standing
                aside and pulled him into the conversation. <persName corresp="recJgMRnt6OpkXR5T"
                    >Lehman</persName> asked <persName corresp="recg40EWOB1iEMjYn"
                    >Vorontsov</persName> whether the Soviet side will make this clear in <rs
                    type="event" corresp="recdBCWoByS1vPFiZ">Geneva</rs>. Will Ambassador <persName
                    corresp="recpzeNUmrT8bK2yc">Obukhov</persName> be given precise guidance that
                the Soviet side is prepared to agree to the 4800 and 3300 <rs
                    corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19" type="topic">sublimits</rs>? <persName
                    corresp="recg40EWOB1iEMjYn">Vorontsov</persName> said, “of course, we will be
                precise.” <persName corresp="recg40EWOB1iEMjYn">Vorontsov</persName> then moved on
                to join <persName corresp="reczYQHQnMCD2hSLc">Shevardnadze</persName>. <persName
                    corresp="recpzeNUmrT8bK2yc">Obukhov</persName> exchanged some pleasantries with
                    <persName corresp="recJgMRnt6OpkXR5T">Lehman</persName> and said that he would
                see <persName corresp="recJgMRnt6OpkXR5T">Lehman</persName> in <rs type="event"
                    corresp="recdBCWoByS1vPFiZ">Geneva</rs>.</p>
            <p>9. Comment: The full intent of the Soviet presentation on <rs
                    corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19" type="topic">sublimits</rs> is not clear. An
                announcement in <gloss target="#t_TASS_1">
                    <orgName corresp="rec6VjZ6vhaTCDp30">TASS</orgName>
                </gloss> recounting the proposal could be read as being consistent with the U.S.
                approach of one way freedom-to-mix. Nevertheless, General Secretary <persName
                    corresp="recXTrNyt2vU9QpAl">Gorbachev</persName>’s presentation implies the
                approach of separate limits on each leg of the <rs corresp="rechRXFB0v2ifZPIR"
                    type="compound-subject">triad</rs> along the lines of the Soviet Union’s force
                structure. That would, of course, be unacceptable. Although <persName
                    corresp="recg40EWOB1iEMjYn">Vorontsov</persName>’s comment is intriguing, he is
                not an expert and may not understand the Soviet proposal. <persName
                    corresp="recg40EWOB1iEMjYn">Vorontsov</persName> is also manipulative and may
                have made his comments as a negotiating tactic. The bottom line remains: the Soviet
                proposal means that their desired force structure after 50-percent <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recHoFOsQcM4e5M4k">reductions</rs> is consistent with the U.S.
                proposal. We could not live with their proposal if it means separate <rs
                    corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19" type="topic">sublimits</rs>, but they could live
                with our proposal as it is presently structured. End comment.</p>
            <p>10. Moscow minimize considered.</p>
            <closer>
                <signed>
                    <persName corresp="recf8o0BSH2MQ1KRY">
                        <hi rendition="simple_bold">
                            <persName corresp="recCK3MZnAvKku4lA">Hanmer</persName>
                        </hi>
                    </persName>
                </signed>
            </closer>
        </body>
